{"cursor":"18389","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour = #EEDD82 name = Santiago MartÃ­nez Delgado image = imagesize = 200px\n| caption = 1948 Photograph birth_name = Santiago MartÃ­nez Delgado birth_date =\n| 1906 birth_place = BogotÃ¡, DC, Colombia death_date = 1954 death_place =\n| Hacienda El Molino, Colombia nationality= Colombian field = Painting training\n| = Chicago Academy of Fine Arts, Frank Lloyd Wright movement = Art Deco,\n| Muralist works = Mural at the Colombian Capitol patrons = Nelson Rockefeller\n| awards = Logan Medal of the arts, SalÃ³n de Artistas Colombianos\n}}\n\n'Santiago MartÃ­nez Delgado' (1906â1954) was a Colombian painter, sculptor, art\nhistorian and writer. He established a reputation as a prominent muralist during\nthe 1940s and is also known for his watercolors, oil paintings, illustrations\nand woodcarvings.\n\nMartÃ­nez attended the Chicago Academy of Fine Arts under the tutelage of Ruth\nVanSickle Ford. \"VanSickle papers\" The Papers of RVF at the Smithsonian\nInstitution. Smithsonian Magazine. Fall/Winter 1980, p. 239, 322, 344 In\n1933, he was awarded the Logan Medal of the arts for his mural at the \"Century\nof Progress\" International Exhibition in Chicago. During these years in Chicago,\nhe produced various illustrations for Esquire Magazine and participated in the\nFederal Art Project. \"He was outed for not being a US citizen along with\nWillen de Kooning\" MartÃ­nez was a disciple of Frank Lloyd Wright at\nTaliesin, where he began to experiment with the Art Deco style. \"Santiago\nMartinez Delgado el Humanista el Colombiano\" Seguros Bolivar1974, p. 29,30\n\nIn Colombia, MartÃ­nez was awarded the gold medal in the 1940 SalÃ³n de Artistas\nColombianos and was again awarded the top prize in 1941. In 1947, Martinez\nDelgado painted the mural at the SalÃ³n ElÃ­ptico in the Colombian Congress\nBuilding, considered one of the greatest murals of the 20th century. MartÃ­nez\nwas then awarded La Orden De Boyaca (Colombia's highest government honor).\nMartinez was at the top of the Latin-American fine-arts scene when he died at\nthe age of 47.\n","linknr":254,"url":"Santiago_Martínez_Delgado","recorded":1375075339,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Santiago_Mart%C3%ADnez_Delgado&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Santiago_Mart%C3%ADnez_Delgado&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Spanish_naming_customs","/wiki/Family_name","/wiki/Bogot%C3%A1","/wiki/Capital_District_(Colombia)","/wiki/Colombia","/wiki/Colombia","/wiki/Colombian_people","/wiki/Painting","/wiki/Chicago_Academy_of_Fine_Arts","/wiki/Frank_Lloyd_Wright","/wiki/Art_Deco","/wiki/Muralist","/wiki/Nelson_Rockefeller","/wiki/Logan_Medal_of_the_arts","/wiki/Sal%C3%B3n_de_Artistas_Colombianos","/wiki/Colombia","/wiki/Art_historian","/wiki/Muralist","/wiki/Chicago_Academy_of_Fine_Arts","/wiki/Ruth_VanSickle_Ford","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Logan_Medal_of_the_arts","/wiki/Century_of_Progress","/wiki/Chicago","/wiki/Esquire_Magazine","/wiki/Federal_Art_Project","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Frank_Lloyd_Wright","/wiki/Taliesin_(studio)","/wiki/Art_Deco","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Sal%C3%B3n_de_Artistas_Colombianos","/wiki/Mural","#Biography","#Ge